{{Infobox family |name = Murdoch |region = Australia; United Kingdom; United States; |origin = [[Pitsligo]], Aberdeenshire, Scotland |ethnicity = [[Scottish Australian]]; [[Anglo-Celtic Australian]]; [[British people|British]]; [[Americans|American]] |members = {{unbulleted list|[[Walter Murdoch|Sir Walter Murdoch]]|[[Keith Murdoch|Sir Keith Murdoch]]|[[Rupert Murdoch]]|[[Elisabeth Murdoch (businesswoman)|Elisabeth Murdoch]] (junior)|[[James Murdoch|James R. Murdoch]]|[[Lachlan Murdoch]]}} |connectedmembers = {{unbulleted list|[[Elisabeth Murdoch (philanthropist)|Dame Elisabeth Murdoch]] (née Greene; 1909–2012)|[[Matthew Freud]]|[[Sarah Murdoch]] (née O'Hare)|[[Wendy Deng Murdoch]]|[[Jerry Hall]]}} }}
Members of the '''Murdoch family''' are prominent as international media proprietors, especially in Australia, the United Kingdom and United States. Some members have also been prominent in the arts, clergy and military in Australia.
Five generations of the family are descended from two [[Scottish Australian|Scottish emigrants to Australia]]: the Reverend James Murdoch (1818–1884), a [[minister (Christianity)|minister]] of the [[Free Church of Scotland (1843–1900)|Free Church of Scotland]] and his wife Helen, née Garden (1826–1905).<ref name="wood">[http://www.wargs.com/other/murdoch.html Michael J Wood, 2005, ''Ancestry of Rupert Murdoch''], William Addams Reitwiesner Genealogical Services (17 August 2013).</ref> Both were from the [[Pitsligo]] area of [[Aberdeenshire]] and emigrated to the [[Victoria, Australia|Colony of Victoria]] in 1884.<ref name="wood"/>{{col-begin|width=100%}}
==History==
[[File:Deakin Uni. acc. MS0001 Murdoch family.jpg|thumb|left|220px|Prof. [[Walter Murdoch]] (left) and family at Point Lonsdale, Victoria, in 1910. His wife, Violet (née Hughston) is upper centre. Their daughter, Catherine – as [[Catherine King (radio broadcaster)|Catherine King]] a prominent broadcaster – is centre right and son William (Will) Murdoch is on the right.]]
===First generation===
Helen and the Rev. James Murdoch had 14 children.<ref name="wood"/>
Their eldest child, the [[Patrick John Murdoch|Rev. Patrick Murdoch]] was born in Pitsligo and raised at [[Rosehearty]], Aberdeenshire.<ref name="wood"/><ref>{{cite book|author=Gunson, Niel|date=1986|title=Murdoch, Patrick John (1850–1940)|work=[[Australian Dictionary of Biography]]}}</ref> He was ordained at [[Cruden Bay|Cruden, Aberdeenshire]], where he also married Annie Brown (in 1882). At the age of 34, Murdoch emigrated with his wife and parents to Victoria. He was a prominent there as a [[Presbyterian]] minister and published several books on theology. Two of Patrick and Annie Murdoch's six children achieved prominence, [[Keith Arthur Murdoch|Sir Keith Murdoch]] and [[Ivon Murdoch|Ivon George Murdoch]].<ref name="wood"/>
Nora Curle Smith, née Murdoch, was born in Pitsligo and married David Curle Smith (1859–1922). A pioneering electrical engineer, David Curle Smith was in charge of the municipal electricity supply at [[Kalgoorlie, Western Australia]] during the early 20th century, invented a pioneering [[electric stove]], which he patented in 1906.<ref>{{cite book |last=Curle Smith |first=H. Nora |others=(Introduction by [[H. A. Willis]].) |title=Thermo–electrical cooking made easy: proved recipes for guidance in the use of the Rational electric cooking stove (D. Curle Smith's patent) |url=http://www.hesperianpress.com/index.php/booklist/2011-06-17-00-41-54/t-titles/458-thermo-electrical-cooking-made-easy1|location=Carlisle, Western Australia|publisher=Hesperian Press|year=2011}}</ref> To promote the stove, Nora Curle Smith wrote the world's [[Electric stove#Kalgoorlie Stove|first cookbook for electric stoves]], which featured 161 recipes and operating instructions for the stove, under the name "H. Nora Curle Smith": ''Thermo-Electrical Cooking Made Easy'' (1907; reprinted 2011). Nora Curle Smith was also a noted painter.{{cn|date=April 2016}}
[[File:Murdoch Building 440 Bower Court 2014 iwelam.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Part of the main campus of [[Murdoch University]], in [[Murdoch, Western Australia|Murdoch]], a suburb of [[Perth, Western Australia]]. Both the university and suburb are named after Sir Walter Murdoch.]]
Sir Walter Murdoch {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KCMG}}, who was born at Rosehearty, was a prominent Australian academic and essayist. He married Violet Catherine Hughston in 1897. Murdoch published his first essay, "The new school of Australian poets", in 1899 and for many years he wrote a weekly column titled "Books and Men" for the ''[[Melbourne Argus]]'' (under the pen name of "Elzevir").<ref name="walter"/> His academic career began with an appointment in 1904 as an assistant lecturer in English at [[Melbourne University]].{{cn|date=April 2016}} In 1913, he was appointed founding Professor of English at the [[University of Western Australia]] (UWA). During the 1920s, his essays were syndicated across Australia through the [[The Herald and Weekly Times|Herald & Weekly Times]] newspaper group run by his nephew, Sir Keith Murdoch (see below). Collections of Walter Murdoch's writings were published in book form from the 1930s onward. He was appointed a [[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George|Companion of the Order of St Michael & St George]] (CMG) in 1939, served as Chancellor of UWA in 1943–48 and was made a Professor Emeritus upon his retirement. Violet Murdoch died in 1952 and 10 years later Murdoch remarried, to Barbara Marshall Cameron. He was appointed a [[Knight Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George|Knight Commander of the Order of St Michael & St George]] (KCMG) in 1964.<ref name="walter">[http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/murdoch-sir-walter-logie-7698 Fred Alexander, 1986, "Murdoch, Sir Walter Logie (1874–1970)", ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'']; accessed 20 August 2013.</ref>
In [[Perth, Western Australia|Perth]], Sir Walter Murdoch is commemorated by the names of both [[Murdoch University]] and the suburb surrounding its main campus: [[Murdoch, Western Australia|Murdoch]].
===Second generation=== [[File:KeithMurdoch.jpg|thumb|right|125px|Sir [[Keith Murdoch]] (1885–1952).]] {{main|Keith Murdoch{{!}}Sir Keith Murdoch|Ivon Murdoch|William David Murdoch|Catherine Helen King}} Keith Arthur Murdoch, later Sir Keith Murdoch, was born in [[West Melbourne, Victoria|West Melbourne]] and grew up in the Melbourne suburb of [[Camberwell, Victoria|Camberwell]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/murdoch-sir-keith-arthur-7693/text13467|author=Serle, Geoffrey|date=1986|title=Murdoch, Sir Keith Arthur (1885–1952)|work=Australian Dictionary of Biography|accessdate=24 October 2013}}</ref> He became prominent as a journalist, while serving as a war correspondent during [[World War I]]. In 1921, Murdoch was appointed chief editor of the ''[[Melbourne Herald]]'' and in 1928 became managing director of its parent company, [[The Herald and Weekly Times|The Herald and Weekly Times Ltd]]. That same year he married Elisabeth Joy Greene (1909–2012), who was later prominent as the philanthropist [[Elisabeth Murdoch (philanthropist)|Dame Elisabeth Murdoch]] {{post-nominals|country=AUS|sep=,|AC|DBE}} (1909–2012). Murdoch was knighted in 1933. During [[World War II]], Sir Keith Murdoch served briefly in an Australian government role, as Director-General of Information.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,795134,00.html|work=Time|title=Censorship Down Under|date=30 December 1940|accessdate=21 August 2013}}</ref>
[[First Lieutenant|Lieutenant]] [[Ivon Murdoch|Ivon George Murdoch]] {{post-nominals|country=AUS|sep=,|MC}} and [[medal bar|bar]], saw action with the [[8th Battalion (Australia)|8th Battalion]] ([[First Australian Imperial Force|AIF]]) on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] during World War I.<ref name="Ivon">{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/in-depth/in-metal-the-deeds-of-men-lie-hidden-but-immortal/2007/11/10/1194329558177.html?page=fullpage|title=Anna King Murdoch: "In metal, the deeds of men lie hidden but immortal"|work=[[The Age]]|date=11 November 2007|accessdate=16 August 2013}}</ref><ref name="Ivon2">{{cite web|url=http://www.awm.gov.au/research/people/nominal_rolls/first_world_war_embarkation/person.asp?p=120584|publisher=Australian War Memorial|title=First World War Embarkation Roll – Ivan George Murdoch|accessdate=6 September 2013}} </ref> Ivon Murdoch achieved the rare distinction of twice being awarded the Military Cross (MC) for bravery; his first resulted from him leading extended night patrols, during March and April 1918, south-east of [[Ypres]] in [[No Man's Land]] and behind [[Empire of Germany|German]] lines, which captured a [[bunker|pillbox]] and returned wounded men to Australian positions.{{cn|date=April 2016}} The second MC was awarded for actions during August 1918 that: successfully defended recently captured German [[field gun]]s near [[Rosières-en-Santerre, France|Rosieres]] and; set up a machine gun [[enfilade]], during the [[Battle of Lihons]] (part of the [[Hundred Days Offensive]]). After the war, Ivon Murdoch was a farmer at [[Wantabadgery, New South Wales]].{{cn|date=April 2016}}
The children of Andrew Chrystal Murdoch and Annie Murdoch (née Esler) included a prominent concert pianist, [[William David Murdoch]] (born 1888, [[Bendigo, Victoria]] – died 1942, [[Holmbury St Mary]], England),{{cn|date=April 2016}}
A daughter of Sir Walter and Violet Murdoch, [[Catherine King (radio broadcaster)|Dr Catherine King (née Murdoch)]] {{post-nominals|country=AUS|sep=,|MBE}} (born 1904, [[Surrey Hills, Victoria]] – died 2000), was a pioneering radio broadcaster in Western Australia.{{cn|date=April 2016}}
===Third generation=== [[File:Rupert Murdoch - WEF Davos 2007.jpg|thumb|right|90px|upright|[[Rupert Murdoch]] at the [[World Economic Forum]] Annual Meeting in [[Davos]], 2007.]] {{main|Rupert Murdoch}} Rupert Murdoch {{post-nominals|country=AUS|sep=,|AC}}, {{post-nominals|country=UK|KSG}}, born in [[Melbourne]], is a major international media proprietor – he chairs two United States-based companies that control most of his assets: [[News Corp]] and [[New Fox]]. Murdoch's career as a media proprietor began in 1952, when he inherited his father's stake in [[News Limited]].<ref name="witzel"/> The company's only major asset was an [[Adelaide, South Australia|Adelaide]] daily newspaper distributed only in South Australia, [[The News (Adelaide)|''The News'']]. During the 1950s and 1960s, News Ltd acquired daily and weekly newspapers, including suburban and provincial publications, throughout Australia and New Zealand. From 1968, Murdoch bought British newspapers, beginning with the weekly ''[[News of the World]]'' and the daily ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]''.<ref Name= "Deals">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2007/jul/18/citynews.pressandpublishing|title=Rupert Murdoch – a lifetime of deals|date=18 July 2007|location=London, UK|work=The Guardian|first=Chris|last=Tryhorn}}</ref>
Murdoch made his first acquisition in the United States in 1973, when he purchased the ''[[San Antonio Express-News]]''. Soon afterwards, he founded a US [[supermarket tabloid]] ''[[Star Magazine|Star]]'', and in 1976, he purchased the ''[[New York Post]]''.<ref name="witzel">{{cite encyclopedia |editor=Witzel, Morgen |editorlink=Morgen Witzel|encyclopedia=The Encyclopedia of the History of American Management|date=2005|location=Bristol, England|publisher=Thoemmes Continuum|page=393}}</ref>
In 1981, Murdoch acquired ''[[The Times]]'' of London and ''[[The Sunday Times]]''. He bought a major stake in [[20th Century Fox]] in 1984, which became the basis of a new US [[free to air]] television network, [[Fox Broadcasting Company]].<ref name="witzel"/> To satisfy a legal requirement that only US citizens could own US television stations, Murdoch became a naturalised US citizen in 1985, and consequently forfeited his Australian citizenship.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Given|first=Jock|title=Foreign Ownership of Media and Telecommunications: an Australian story|journal=Media & Arts Law Review|volume=7|issue=4|page=253|date=December 2002}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=The World's Billionaires No.73 Rupert Murdoch|newspaper=Forbes|date=7 October 2007|url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2007/10/07billionaires_Rupert-Murdoch_639W.html|accessdate=8 October 2009}}</ref>
During the 1980s and 1990s, Murdoch became involved in [[pay television]] interests throughout the world, including [[STAR TV]] and [[Tata Sky]] in Asia and [[BSkyB]], [[Sky Italia]] and [[Sky Deutschland]] in Europe. NewsCorp also came to control both a major international publishing house [[HarperCollins]], and [[Dow Jones & Company]], which includes ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''.{{cn|date=April 2016}}
Rupert Murdoch has been married four times and has six children: * 1956–1967: to Patricia Booker, a flight attendant from Melbourne, with whom he had one child, Mrs Prudence MacLeod.<ref name="Examiner">{{cite news|url=http://www.examiner.ie/business/business-features/how-safe-is-the-murdoch-empire-160545.html|title=How safe is the Murdoch empire?|date=9 July 2011|work=The Irish Examiner|accessdate=17 August 2013}}</ref><ref Name="Wherenow">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/so-where-does-rupert-murdoch-go-from-here-500802.html|title=So where does Rupert Murdoch go from here?|date=31 July 2005|work=The Independent|location=London, UK|accessdate=17 August 2013}}</ref><ref name=IBT/> * 1967–1999: to [[Anna Murdoch Mann|Anna Torv]] (later Anna Murdoch Mann; born 1944),<ref name="Examiner"/> a Scottish journalist of Estonian descent, who worked on Murdoch's Sydney ''[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|Daily Telegraph]]'', later published two novels and is the aunt of actress [[Anna Torv]].<ref name=IBT>{{cite news|title=Rupert Murdoch and His Family|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/articles/177013/20110709/rupert-murdoch-james-murdoc-news-corp.htm|work=International Business Times|accessdate=17 August 2013|date=9 July 2011}}</ref> Torv and Murdoch had three children, [[Elisabeth Murdoch (businesswoman)|Elisabeth Murdoch junior]] (b. 1968), [[Lachlan Murdoch|Lachlan Keith Murdoch]] (b. 1971) and [[James Murdoch (media executive)|James Rupert Jacob Murdoch]], also known as James R. Murdoch (b. 1972).<ref name="Examiner"/><ref Name= "Wherenow"/> * 1999–2013 to [[Wendi Deng]], a Chinese-US media executive and company director,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/jul/30/business/fi-murdoch30|title=Murdoch's Heir Apparent Abruptly Resigns His Post|date=30 July 2005|work=Los Angeles Times|first=Sallie|last=Hofmeister|accessdate=17 August 2013}}</ref> They have two daughters. * 2016–present to [[Jerry Hall]].{{cn|date=April 2016}}
===Fourth generation=== [[File:Lachlan Murdoch in May 2013.jpg|thumb|100px|upright|[[Lachlan Murdoch]].]] [[File:James Murdoch 2008- NRKbeta.jpg|thumb|200px|upright|[[James Murdoch (media executive)|James Murdoch.]]]]
'''Prue Murdoch''' (born in [[Adelaide, South Australia|Adelaide]]) has held directorial roles within the News Corporation empire. She has been married twice: * 1985–c. 1986, to British financier [[Crispin Odey]] * since 1989, to: British media executive Charles Alasdair MacLeod (usually known as Alasdair MacLeod). Both Prue and Alasdair MacLeod hold or have held directorial and/or executive roles within the News Corporation empire. They have three children,<ref name="heirs">[http://www.maynereport.com/articles/2011/07/31-1555-6211.html Stephen Mayne, "Tracking the Murdoch heirs", ''The Mayne Report'', 2011] (17 August 2013).</ref> James MacLeod (b. 1991), Angus MacLeod (b. 1993) and Clementine MacLeod (b. 1996).
'''[[Elisabeth Murdoch (businesswoman)|Elisabeth Murdoch]]''' (born in Sydney), is a media executive and company director and has been married twice. * 1993–1998: to '''[[Elkin Kwesi Pianim]]''', a [[Ghanaian people|Ghanaian]] banker, with whom she had two children,<ref name="heirs"/> Cornelia Pianim (b. 1994) and Anna Pianim (b. 1997); * Since 2001: to British public relations specialist '''[[Matthew Freud]]''' (the son of former MP Sir [[Clement Freud]], and a great-grandson of [[Sigmund Freud]]), with whom she had two children,<ref name="heirs"/> Charlotte Emma Freud (b. 2000) and Samson Murdoch Freud (b. 2007).
'''[[Lachlan Murdoch]]''' (born in London), is a media executive and company director; he married the British-Australian model and actress '''[[Sarah Murdoch]]''', née O'Hare (b. 1972) in 1999; they have three children,<ref name="heirs"/><ref name="brewster">[http://www.kittybrewster.com/ancestry/murdoch.htm Sir William Arbuthnot, 2011, ''The Genealogy of the Murdoch Family.''] (9 May 2014).</ref> Kalan Alexander Murdoch (b. 2004), Aidan Patrick Murdoch (b. 2006) and Aerin Elisabeth Murdoch (b. 2010).
'''[[James Murdoch|James R. Murdoch]]''' (born in London), is a media executive and company director. In 2000, he married the US public relations specialist and climate change activist Kathryn Hufschmid. They have three children,<ref name="heirs"/> Anneka Murdoch (b. 2003), Walter Murdoch (b. 2006) and Emerson Murdoch (b. 2008).
